text: Fig. 9. Migration of rhodamine B marker on three separate TLC plates. Disances were measured to the center of the zone.

Fig. 10. Picture showing the 8.5 migration of Rhodamine B in 30 . Notice how the spot stays in the center of the TLC plate. The solute zone has been digitally enhanced by intensifying the pink solute color to a deeper red (for visualization purposes) without compromising the zone shape or diffusion characteristics. an 8.5 migration in 30 where the solute zone stays in the center of the 2.5 wide plate with zone dispersion (zone length of 2.6 ) primarily in the direction of voltage drop. This assures that EOF is only in the direction between positive and negative source electrodes, and there are no localized gradients within the width of the 2.5 TLC plate. Analysis of this spot yielded well over 10,000 plates. This was not a point injection and the spot width was not measured prior to PPEC affecting the measure of zone dispersion, therefore over-estimating the actual band broadening. Also, the final zone width was estimated with a ruler and visual inspection, under-estimating the actual band broadening. There may have also been some zone refocusing mechanism as the zone migrated past each reader electrode, helping keep the compact zone shape, but the migration rate (Fig. 9) would not have been so reproducible. Factoring in both under and over-estimations, we feel confident that this zone is still measuring over 8000 theoretical plates. This was not typical for efficiencies seen in PPEC experiments, normally producing about half that number of theoretical plates. Better understanding of the many experimental parameters will hopefully make this a more common measure of efficiency.
